			    function FOL_GTM_PushEvent(category,action,label,network,eventType,oCustomVarsIn) {
			    	var type = (eventType) ? eventType : 'std',
			    		defaultEvent = {
			    			'event': 'event',
							'eventCategory': category,
							'eventAction': action,
							'eventLabel': label
			    		};
			    	
			    	if (category.toLowerCase() == 'social') {
			    		defaultEvent['eventSocialNetwork'] = network;
		                dataLayer.push(defaultEvent);
		                dataLayer.push({'eventSocialNetwork': void 0});  
			    	} else if (type == 'nonInteraction') {
			    		defaultEvent['eventNonInteraction'] = 1;
	                    dataLayer.push(defaultEvent);
	                    dataLayer.push({'eventNonInteraction': void 0});
			    	} else if ( typeof(oCustomVarsIn) == "object" ) {
			    		var oCustomVars = {};
			    		for (var param in oCustomVarsIn) {
		                    oCustomVars[param] = oCustomVarsIn[param];
		                }
			    		if ( type == "std" ) {
				    		for (var param in defaultEvent) {
				    			oCustomVars[param] = defaultEvent[param];
				    		}
			    		}		    		
						dataLayer.push(oCustomVars);					
						for (var param in oCustomVars) {
							oCustomVars[param] = void 0;
						}					
						dataLayer.push(oCustomVars);					
			    	} else {
	                    dataLayer.push(defaultEvent);
	                }
			    }
			    function FOL_GTM_PushSiteSearch(searchterm,category) { /*dataLayer.push({'event': 'search','siteSearchTerm': searchterm,'siteSearchCategory': category});*/ }
			    function FOL_GTM_VirtPageview(category,agof) {
			        var pageCategory = (category) ? category : "rubrik";
	                dataLayer.push({
	                    'event': 'virtualPage',
	                    'pageCategory': pageCategory,
	                    'pageIVW_AGOF': agof,
	                    'virtualPage': 'true',
	                    'virtualPagePath': 'politik/videos_' + category 
	                    });
	            }

<div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Question">
    
			<div id="question-header">
                <h1 itemprop="name"><a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2163045/how-to-remove-line-breaks-from-a-file-in-java" class="question-hyperlink">How to remove line breaks from a file in Java?</a></h1>
		</div>
			<div id="mainbar">

			

<div class="question" data-questionid="2163045" id="question">

    
            <div class="everyonelovesstackoverflow adzerk-vote" id="adzerk631661530"><iframe scrolling="no" id="ados_frame_adzerk631661530_1725113" frameborder="0" height="90" width="728"></iframe><img src="http://engine.adzerk.net/i.gif?&amp;s=AlvDHcqoJGvr1jT9VqjPzCNrC_Y" style="position:absolute;" border="0" height="0px" width="0px"></div>    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This question shows research effort; it is useful and clear">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">118</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This question does not show any research effort; it is unclear or not useful">down vote</a>

        <a title="Click to mark as favorite question (click again to undo)" class="star-off" href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2163045/how-to-remove-line-breaks-from-a-file-in-java#">favorite</a>
        <div class="favoritecount"><b>19</b></div>


</div>

            </td>
            
<td class="postcell">
<div>
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">

<p>How can I replace all line breaks from a string in Java in such a way
 that will work on Windows and Linux (ie no OS specific problems of 
carriage return/line feed/new line etc.)?</p>

<p>I've tried (note readFileAsString is a function that reads a text file into a String):          </p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">String</span><span class="pln"> text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> readFileAsString</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"textfile.txt"</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
text</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replace</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>but this doesn't seem to work.</p>

<p>How can this be done?</p>
    </div>
    <div class="post-taglist">
        <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/java" class="post-tag js-gps-track" title="show questions tagged 'java'" rel="tag">java</a> <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/string" class="post-tag js-gps-track" title="show questions tagged 'string'" rel="tag">string</a> <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/newline" class="post-tag js-gps-track" title="show questions tagged 'newline'" rel="tag">newline</a> <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/line-breaks" class="post-tag js-gps-track" title="show questions tagged 'line-breaks'" rel="tag">line-breaks</a> 
    </div>

				<div id="answers-header">
					<div class="subheader answers-subheader">
						<h2>
								12 Answers
                                
						</h2>
						<div>
							<div id="tabs">
        <a class="youarehere" href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2163045/how-to-remove-line-breaks-from-a-file-in-java?answertab=active#tab-top" data-nav-xhref="" title="Answers with the latest activity first" data-value="active" data-shortcut="A">

            oldest</a>
        <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2163045/how-to-remove-line-breaks-from-a-file-in-java?answertab=votes#tab-top" data-nav-xhref="" title="Answers with the highest score first" data-value="votes" data-shortcut="V">

<a name="2163056"></a>
<div id="answer-2163056" class="answer accepted-answer" data-answerid="2163056" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer" itemprop="acceptedAnswer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">210</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>



        <span class="vote-accepted-on load-accepted-answer-date" title="loading when this answer was accepted...">accepted</span>

</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<p>You need to set <code>text</code> to the results of <code>text.replace()</code>:</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">String</span><span class="pln"> text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> readFileAsString</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"textfile.txt"</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> text</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replace</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">).</span><span class="pln">replace</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\r"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>This is necessary because Strings are immutable -- calling <code>replace</code> doesn't change the original String, it returns a new one that's been changed.  If you don't assign the result to <code>text</code>, then that new String is lost and garbage collected.</p>

<p>As for getting the newline String for any environment -- that is available by calling <code>System.getProperty("line.separator")</code>.</p>
    </div>
    <table class="fw">
    <tbody><tr>
    <td class="vt">

            <div class="comment-body">
                <span class="comment-copy">+1, correct. As to the reason: String is <b>immutable</b>. The <code>replace()</code> method <b>returns</b> the desired result. Also see the API docs: <a href="http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#replace%28java.lang.CharSequence,%20java.lang.CharSequence%29" rel="nofollow">java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/…</a> <i>Edit:</i> ah you already edited that yourself in afterwards :)</span>
                    –&nbsp;<a href="http://stackoverflow.com/users/157882/balusc" title="662,790 reputation" class="comment-user">BalusC</a>

            <div class="comment-body">
                <span class="comment-copy">Perhaps <code>text = text.replace("\r\n", " ").replace("\n", " ");</code> is a better solution: otherwise words will be "glued" to each other (without the single-space replacement).</span>
                    –&nbsp;<a href="http://stackoverflow.com/users/50476/bart-kiers" title="103,709 reputation" class="comment-user">Bart Kiers</a>
                <span class="comment-date" dir="ltr"><a class="comment-link" href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2163045/how-to-remove-line-breaks-from-a-file-in-java#comment2107418_2163056"><span title="2010-01-29 15:54:04Z" class="relativetime-clean">Jan 29 '10 at 15:54</span></a></span>

        <td class="comment-text">
            <div class="comment-body">
                <span class="comment-copy">Yeah, that's possible.  It 
all depends on what type of data you're trying to modify.  Sometimes 
(for data such as COBOL copybooks) you don't want there to be any spaces
 between the lines.</span>
                    –&nbsp;<a href="http://stackoverflow.com/users/179233/kaleb-brasee" title="33,450 reputation" class="comment-user">Kaleb Brasee</a>
                <span class="comment-date" dir="ltr"><a class="comment-link" href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2163045/how-to-remove-line-breaks-from-a-file-in-java#comment2107440_2163056"><span title="2010-01-29 15:56:38Z" class="relativetime-clean">Jan 29 '10 at 15:56</span></a></span>

<a name="38160859"></a>
<div id="answer-38160859" class="answer" data-answerid="38160859" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">0</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>




</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<p>I find it odd that (Apache) <a href="https://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-lang/apidocs/org/apache/commons/lang3/StringUtils.html" rel="nofollow">StringUtils</a> wasn't covered here yet.</p>

<p>you can remove all newlines (or any other occurences of a substring for that matter) from a string using the <code>.replace</code> method</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">StringUtils</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replace</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="pln">myString</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">"\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>This line will replace all newlines with the empty string. </p>

<p>because newline is technically a character you can optionally use the <code>.replaceChars</code> method that will replace characters</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">StringUtils</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceChars</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="pln">myString</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">'\n'</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">''</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>
    </div>
    <table class="fw">
    <tbody><tr>
    <td class="vt">

<a name="34934604"></a>
<div id="answer-34934604" class="answer" data-answerid="34934604" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">0</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>




</div>

<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<p>You can use apache commons IOUtils to iterate through the line and 
append each line to StringBuilder. And don't forget to close the 
InputStream </p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">StringBuilder</span><span class="pln"> sb </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="kwd">new</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="typ">StringBuilder</span><span class="pun">();</span><span class="pln">
    </span><span class="typ">FileInputStream</span><span class="pln"> fin</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="kwd">new</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="typ">FileInputStream</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"textfile.txt"</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
    </span><span class="typ">LineIterator</span><span class="pln"> lt</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="typ">IOUtils</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">lineIterator</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="pln">fin</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">"utf-8"</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
    </span><span class="kwd">while</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="pln">lt</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">hasNext</span><span class="pun">())</span><span class="pln">
    </span><span class="pun">{</span><span class="pln">
       sb</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">append</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="pln">lt</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">nextLine</span><span class="pun">());</span><span class="pln">
    </span><span class="pun">}</span><span class="pln">
   </span><span class="typ">String</span><span class="pln"> text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> sb</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">toString</span><span class="pun">();</span><span class="pln">
  </span><span class="typ">IOUtils</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">closeQuitely</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="pln">fin</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>
    </div>
    <table class="fw">
    <tbody><tr>
    <td class="vt">

<a name="2163104"></a>
<div id="answer-2163104" class="answer" data-answerid="2163104" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">10</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>




</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<p>If you want to remove only line terminators that are valid on the current OS, you could do this:</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="pln">text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> text</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="typ">System</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">getProperty</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"line.separator"</span><span class="pun">),</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>If you want to make sure you remove any line separators, you can do it like this:</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="pln">text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> text</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\r|\\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>Or, slightly more verbose, but less regexy:</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="pln">text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> text</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\r"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">).</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>
    </div>
    <table class="fw">
    <tbody><tr>

        <td class="comment-text">
            <div class="comment-body">
                <span class="comment-copy">To avoid gluing word together (as discussed in comments to Kaleb's answer) the regex approach could be modified to <code>text.replaceAll("(\\r|\\n)+", " ")</code> and (assuming greedy is default in Java?) you will have a solution with just <i>one</i> space for each sequence of new line chars.</span>
                    –&nbsp;<a href="http://stackoverflow.com/users/121364/j%c3%b8rn-schou-rode" title="25,016 reputation" class="comment-user">Jørn Schou-Rode</a>
                <span class="comment-date" dir="ltr"><a class="comment-link" href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2163045/how-to-remove-line-breaks-from-a-file-in-java#comment2107651_2163104"><span title="2010-01-29 16:20:12Z" class="relativetime-clean">Jan 29 '10 at 16:20</span></a></span>

<div id="answer-24960480" class="answer" data-answerid="24960480" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">5</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>




</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="pln">str </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> str</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\r\\n|\\r|\\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">" "</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>Worked perfectly for me after searching a lot, having failed with every other line.</p>
    </div>

        <div class="-flair">
            <span class="reputation-score" title="reputation score " dir="ltr">51</span><span title="1 silver badge"><span class="badge2"></span><span class="badgecount">1</span></span><span title="1 bronze badge"><span class="badge3"></span><span class="badgecount">1</span></span>
        </div>

    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">

</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<p>This would be efficient I guess</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">String</span><span class="pln"> s</span><span class="pun">;</span><span class="pln">
s</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"[\\r\\n]+"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">)</span></code></pre>

<p><em>edited for syntax highlight</em></p>

<div id="answer-13306123" class="answer" data-answerid="13306123" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">0</span>

</div>

<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<p>Try doing this:</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="pln"> textValue</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> textValue</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
 textValue</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> textValue</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\t"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
 textValue</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> textValue</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
 textValue</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> textValue</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\t"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
 textValue</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> textValue</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\r"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
 textValue</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> textValue</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\r"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
 textValue</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> textValue</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\r\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
 textValue</span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> textValue</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\r\\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>
    </div>

<a name="2163204"></a>
<div id="answer-2163204" class="answer" data-answerid="2163204" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">148</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>




</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<p>As noted in other answers, your code is not working <em>primarily</em> because <code>String.replace(...)</code>
 does not change the target String.  (It can't - Java strings are 
immutable!)  What it actually does is creates a new String with the 
characters changed as required.  But your code then throws away that 
String ...</p>

<hr>

<p>Here are some possible solutions.  Which one is most correct depends on what exactly you are trying to do.</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="com">// <a class='hashtag' href='+'>#1</a></span><span class="pln">
text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> text</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replace</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>Simply removes all the newline characters.  This does not cope with Windows or Mac line terminations.</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="com">// <a class='hashtag' href='+'>#2</a></span><span class="pln">
text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> text</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replace</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="typ">System</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">getProperty</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"line.separator"</span><span class="pun">),</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>Removes all line terminators for the current platform.  This does not
 cope with the case where you are trying to process (for example) a UNIX
 file on Windows, or vice versa.</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="com">// <a class='hashtag' href='+'>#3</a></span><span class="pln">
text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> text</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\r|\\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>Removes all Windows, UNIX or Mac line terminators.  However, if the input file is text, this will concatenate words; e.g.</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">Goodbye</span><span class="pln"> cruel
world</span><span class="pun">.</span></code></pre>

<p>becomes</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">Goodbye</span><span class="pln"> cruelworld</span><span class="pun">.</span></code></pre>

<p>So you might actually want to do this:</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="com">// <a class='hashtag' href='+'>#4</a></span><span class="pln">
text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> text</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\\r\\n|\\r|\\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">" "</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>which replaces each line terminator with a space.</p>
    </div>
    <table class="fw">
    <tbody><tr>
    <td class="vt">

    <td class="post-signature" align="right">

        </td>
        <td class="comment-text">
            <div class="comment-body">
                <span class="comment-copy">Good point, I was thinking of
 using this method to replace system line breaks in a string from a 
textbox with HTML &lt;br /&gt; tags.</span>
                    –&nbsp;<a href="http://stackoverflow.com/users/549510/kingsolmn" title="1,236 reputation" class="comment-user">Kingsolmn</a>
                <span class="comment-date" dir="ltr"><a class="comment-link" href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2163045/how-to-remove-line-breaks-from-a-file-in-java#comment20161482_2163204"><span title="2013-01-23 04:03:41Z" class="relativetime-clean">Jan 23 '13 at 4:03</span></a></span>

newlines, vertical tabs and spaces with one space. + is for more than 
one occurance.</span>

<a name="12208919"></a>
<div id="answer-12208919" class="answer" data-answerid="12208919" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">0</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>




</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">String</span><span class="pln"> text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> readFileAsString</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"textfile.txt"</span><span class="pun">).</span><span class="pln">replaceAll</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>Even though the definition of trim() in oracle website is 
"Returns a copy of the string, with leading and trailing whitespace omitted."</p>

<p>it omits new line character as well as leading space.</p>

<p>In short
<code>String text = readFileAsString("textfile.txt").trim();</code> will also work for you.(Checked with Java6)</p>
    </div>
    <table class="fw">
    <tbody><tr>

<a name="2163543"></a>
<div id="answer-2163543" class="answer" data-answerid="2163543" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">2</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>




</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<p>You may want to read your file with a <code>BufferedReader</code>. This class can break input into individual lines, which you can assemble at will. The way <code>BufferedReader</code>
 operates recognizes line ending conventions of the Linux, Windows and 
MacOS worlds automatically, regardless of the current platform.</p>

<p>Hence:</p>

<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">BufferedReader</span><span class="pln"> br </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="kwd">new</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="typ">BufferedReader</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="pln">
    </span><span class="kwd">new</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="typ">InputStreamReader</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"textfile.txt"</span><span class="pun">));</span><span class="pln">
</span><span class="typ">StringBuilder</span><span class="pln"> sb </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="kwd">new</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="typ">StringBuilder</span><span class="pun">();</span><span class="pln">
</span><span class="kwd">for</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="pun">(;;)</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="pun">{</span><span class="pln">
    </span><span class="typ">String</span><span class="pln"> line </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> br</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">readLine</span><span class="pun">();</span><span class="pln">
    </span><span class="kwd">if</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="pln">line </span><span class="pun">==</span><span class="pln"> </span><span class="kwd">null</span><span class="pun">)</span><span class="pln">
        </span><span class="kwd">break</span><span class="pun">;</span><span class="pln">
    sb</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">append</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="pln">line</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">
    sb</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">append</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">' '</span><span class="pun">);</span><span class="pln">   </span><span class="com">// SEE BELOW</span><span class="pln">
</span><span class="pun">}</span><span class="pln">
</span><span class="typ">String</span><span class="pln"> text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> sb</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">toString</span><span class="pun">();</span></code></pre>

<p>Note that <code>readLine()</code> does not include the line 
terminator in the returned string. The code above appends a space to 
avoid gluing together the last word of a line and the first word of the 
next line.</p>
    </div>
    <table class="fw">
    <tbody><tr>

<a name="2163074"></a>
<div id="answer-2163074" class="answer" data-answerid="2163074" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">3</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>




</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="typ">String</span><span class="pln"> text </span><span class="pun">=</span><span class="pln"> readFileAsString</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"textfile.txt"</span><span class="pun">).</span><span class="pln">replace</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"\n"</span><span class="pun">,</span><span class="str">""</span><span class="pun">);</span></code></pre>

<p>.replace returns a new string, strings in Java are Immutable.</p>
    </div>

<a name="2163078"></a>
<div id="answer-2163078" class="answer" data-answerid="2163078" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Answer">
    <table>
        <tbody><tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
        
        <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
        <span itemprop="upvoteCount" class="vote-count-post ">6</span>
        <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>




</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text" itemprop="text">
<p>Linebreaks are not the same under windows/linux/mac. You should use <a href="http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.5.0/docs/api/java/lang/System.html#getProperties%28%29">System.getProperties</a> with the attribute line.separator.</p>
    </div>
    <table class="fw">
    <tbody><tr>

Ctrl+H" id="wmd-heading-button" style="left: 275px;" class="wmd-button"><span style="background-position: -160px 0px;"></span></li><li title="Horizontal Rule &lt;hr&gt; Ctrl+R" id="wmd-hr-button" style="left: 300px;" class="wmd-button"><span style="background-position: -180px 0px;"></span></li><li style="left: 346px;" id="wmd-spacer3" class="wmd-spacer wmd-spacer3"></li><li title="Undo - Ctrl+Z" id="wmd-undo-button" style="left: 350px;" class="wmd-button"><span style="background-position: -200px -20px;"></span></li><li title="Redo - Ctrl+Y" id="wmd-redo-button" style="left: 375px;" class="wmd-button"><span style="background-position: -220px -20px;"></span></li><li title="Markdown Editing Help" style="right: 0px;" id="wmd-help-button" class="wmd-button wmd-help-button"><span style="background-position: -240px 0px;"></span></li></ul></div>

[14:55:17 12.07.16] Einkommender Beitrag:
Text: Stack Exchange Inbox Reputation and Badges 144 14 help Stack Overflow Questions Jobs Tags Users Badges Ask Question How to remove line breaks from a file in Java? up vote 118 down vote favorite 19 How can I replace all line breaks from a string in Java in such a way that will work on Windows and Linux (ie no OS specific problems of carriage return/line feed/new line etc.)? I've tried (note readFileAsString is a function that reads a text file into a String): String text = readFileAsString("textfile.txt"); text.replace("\n", ""); but this doesn't seem to work. How can this be done? java string newline line-breaks shareeditflag edited Aug 10 '11 at 14:32 Jarrod Roberson 42.7k1599176 asked Jan 29 '10 at 15:44 tree-hacker 1,47172035      Do you want to eliminate all line breaks? Or you want to uniformize them to a standard solution? – helios Jan 29 '10 at 15:48 3   Oh, if you want to delete all linefeeds, remove all \n AND all \r (because Windows linebreak is \r\n). – helios Jan 29 '10 at 15:49 add a comment start a bounty 12 Answers active oldest votes up vote 210 down vote accepted You need to set text to the results of text.replace(): String text = readFileAsString("textfile.txt"); text = text.replace("\n", "").replace("\r", ""); This is necessary because Strings are immutable -- calling replace doesn't change the original String, it returns a new one that's been changed. If you don't assign the result to text, then that new String is lost and garbage collected. As for getting the newline String for any environment -- that is available by calling System.getProperty("line.separator"). shareeditflag edited Aug 6 '12 at 23:59 Community♦ 1 answered Jan 29 '10 at 15:47 Kaleb Brasee 33.5k77391 1   +1, correct. As to the reason: String is immutable. The replace() method returns the desired result. Also see the API docs: java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/… Edit: ah you already edited that yourself in afterwards :) – BalusC Jan 29 '10 at 15:49 37   Perhaps text = text.replace("\r\n", " ").replace("\n", " "); is a better solution: otherwise words will be "glued" to each other (without the single-space replacement). – Bart Kiers Jan 29 '10 at 15:54      Yeah, that's possible. It all depends on what type of data you're trying to modify. Sometimes (for data such as COBOL copybooks) you don't want there to be any spaces between the lines. – Kaleb Brasee Jan 29 '10 at 15:56      True, it all depends on what the OP is trying to do. – Bart Kiers Jan 29 '10 at 15:58      You could also use square brackets to match newlines properly for any OS: .replaceAll("[\\r\\n]+", "") – Yeti Apr 26 at 14:48 add a comment up vote 0 down vote I find it odd that (Apache) StringUtils wasn't covered here yet. you can remove all newlines (or any other occurences of a substring for that matter) from a string using the .replace method StringUtils.replace(myString, "\n", ""); This line will replace all newlines with the empty string. because newline is technically a character you can optionally use the .replaceChars method that will replace characters StringUtils.replaceChars(myString, '\n', ''); shareeditflag answered Jul 2 at 13:45 svarog 1,73021630 add a comment up vote 0 down vote You can use apache commons IOUtils to iterate through the line and append each line to StringBuilder. And don't forget to close the InputStream StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(); FileInputStream fin=new FileInputStream("textfile.txt"); LineIterator lt=IOUtils.lineIterator(fin, "utf-8"); while(lt.hasNext()) { sb.append(lt.nextLine()); } String text = sb.toString(); IOUtils.closeQuitely(fin); shareeditflag answered Jan 21 at 21:22 Shravan Ramamurthy 17418 add a comment up vote 10 down vote If you want to remove only line terminators that are valid on the current OS, you could do this: text = text.replaceAll(System.getProperty("line.separator"), ""); If you want to make sure you remove any line separators, you can do it like this: text = text.replaceAll("\\r|\\n", ""); Or, slightly more verbose, but less regexy: text = text.replaceAll("\\r", "").replaceAll("\\n", ""); shareeditflag edited Mar 18 '15 at 11:35 Marek Jeszka 216 answered Jan 29 '10 at 15:52 Fabian Steeg 31.7k560100 1   To avoid gluing word together (as discussed in comments to Kaleb's answer) the regex approach could be modified to text.replaceAll("(\\r|\\n)+", " ") and (assuming greedy is default in Java?) you will have a solution with just one space for each sequence of new line chars. – Jørn Schou-Rode Jan 29 '10 at 16:20 add a comment up vote 5 down vote str = str.replaceAll("\\r\\n|\\r|\\n", " "); Worked perfectly for me after searching a lot, having failed with every other line. shareeditflag answered Jul 25 '14 at 16:38 Renán D 5111 add a comment up vote 2 down vote This would be efficient I guess String s; s.replaceAll("[\\r\\n]+", "") edited for syntax highlight shareeditflag edited Apr 3 '14 at 20:07 answered Mar 9 '13 at 17:16 Dincer 1708 add a comment up vote 0 down vote Try doing this: textValue= textValue.replaceAll("\n", ""); textValue= textValue.replaceAll("\t", ""); textValue= textValue.replaceAll("\\n", ""); textValue= textValue.replaceAll("\\t", ""); textValue= textValue.replaceAll("\r", ""); textValue= textValue.replaceAll("\\r", ""); textValue= textValue.replaceAll("\r\n", ""); textValue= textValue.replaceAll("\\r\\n", ""); shareeditflag edited Nov 9 '12 at 10:40 Ofir Farchy 2,58521843 answered Nov 9 '12 at 10:18 seyf 251 2   if you replace \n there is no \r\n anymore if you replace \n and there is an \\n it will be replaced so only the \ will remain. – Rob Nov 9 '12 at 10:39 add a comment up vote 148 down vote As noted in other answers, your code is not working primarily because String.replace(...) does not change the target String. (It can't - Java strings are immutable!) What it actually does is creates a new String with the characters changed as required. But your code then throws away that String ... Here are some possible solutions. Which one is most correct depends on what exactly you are trying to do. // #1 text = text.replace("\n", ""); Simply removes all the newline characters. This does not cope with Windows or Mac line terminations. // #2 text = text.replace(System.getProperty("line.separator"), ""); Removes all line terminators for the current platform. This does not cope with the case where you are trying to process (for example) a UNIX file on Windows, or vice versa. // #3 text = text.replaceAll("\\r|\\n", ""); Removes all Windows, UNIX or Mac line terminators. However, if the input file is text, this will concatenate words; e.g. Goodbye cruel world. becomes Goodbye cruelworld. So you might actually want to do this: // #4 text = text.replaceAll("\\r\\n|\\r|\\n", " "); which replaces each line terminator with a space. shareeditflag edited Oct 13 '12 at 6:26 answered Jan 29 '10 at 16:07 Stephen C 374k41388714      The 3rd option is the best given that the origin of a text file may be agnostic. – trillions Dec 21 '12 at 5:43      Using the "System.getProperty("line.seperator")" approach would be the best to be as system agnostic as possible. Great answer, thank you! – Kingsolmn Jan 22 '13 at 19:08 2   @Kingsolmn - actually it depends what you mean by agnostic. What if you need to be agnostic of the system that created the file; i.e. if you can't assume that it was created on "this" system? – Stephen C Jan 22 '13 at 23:39      Good point, I was thinking of using this method to replace system line breaks in a string from a textbox with HTML <br /> tags. – Kingsolmn Jan 23 '13 at 4:03 2   How about text.replaceAll("\\s+", " "); which should replace all tabs, returns, newlines, vertical tabs and spaces with one space. + is for more than one occurance. – webDeveloper Nov 24 '14 at 14:50 add a comment |  show 3 more comments up vote 0 down vote String text = readFileAsString("textfile.txt").replaceAll("\n", ""); Even though the definition of trim() in oracle website is "Returns a copy of the string, with leading and trailing whitespace omitted." it omits new line character as well as leading space. In short String text = readFileAsString("textfile.txt").trim(); will also work for you.(Checked with Java6) shareeditflag edited Sep 28 '12 at 20:40 andrewsi 10.2k112442 answered Aug 31 '12 at 4:27 MukeshKoshyM 1 add a comment up vote 2 down vote You may want to read your file with a BufferedReader. This class can break input into individual lines, which you can assemble at will. The way BufferedReader operates recognizes line ending conventions of the Linux, Windows and MacOS worlds automatically, regardless of the current platform. Hence: BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader( new InputStreamReader("textfile.txt")); StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(); for (;;) { String line = br.readLine(); if (line == null) break; sb.append(line); sb.append(' '); // SEE BELOW } String text = sb.toString(); Note that readLine() does not include the line terminator in the returned string. The code above appends a space to avoid gluing together the last word of a line and the first word of the next line. shareeditflag answered Jan 29 '10 at 16:57 Thomas Pornin 49.7k889145 add a comment up vote 3 down vote String text = readFileAsString("textfile.txt").replace("\n",""); .replace returns a new string, strings in Java are Immutable. shareeditflag edited Jan 29 '10 at 15:56 Bart Kiers 104k20185214 answered Jan 29 '10 at 15:49 Viktor Klang 18.9k23351 add a comment up vote 6 down vote Linebreaks are not the same under windows/linux/mac. You should use System.getProperties with the attribute line.separator. shareeditflag answered Jan 29 '10 at 15:49 Aif 6,6781428 add a comment Your Answer   community wiki Not the answer you're looking for?      <div class="post_title">
      <h1>JavaFX List View - Get currently selected item's index?</h1>
      <span class="pt_info pre1"> <span id="pubtime_gg">February 12</span><span id="hitcount">Hits:<strong>18</strong></span></span>
     </div>
     <div class="con-recom">

     <div id="paragraph" class="post_content">
<p>I'm trying to implement a feature and I need the index number of the currently selected item in the list view. So if it's 4th on the list I need a method that will return 3 because I need to edit the corresponding object in an ArrayList.</p>
<p>How can I do this?</p>
     </div>
     <div class="con-recom">
      <div class="bx-recom4">

	 	 <div id="re_paragraph" class="post_re_content">
	 <h2>Answers</h2>
	 
<p>Use</p>
<pre><code>listView.getSelectionModel().getSelectedIndex();
</code>
</pre>	 </div>

      JavaFX List View - Get currently selected item's index?     </div>
     <div class="post_title">
      <h1>JavaFX List View - Get currently selected item's index?</h1>
      <span class="pt_info pre1"> <span id="pubtime_gg">February 12</span><span id="hitcount">Hits:<strong>18</strong></span></span>
     </div>
     <div class="con-recom">
      <div class="bx-recom3">

      </div>
     </div>
     <div id="paragraph" class="post_content">
<p>I'm trying to implement a feature and I need the index number of the currently selected item in the list view. So if it's 4th on the list I need a method that will return 3 because I need to edit the corresponding object in an ArrayList.</p>
<p>How can I do this?</p>
     </div>
     <div class="con-recom">
      <div class="bx-recom4">
       <script type="text/javascript">

	 	 <div id="re_paragraph" class="post_re_content">
	 <h2>Answers</h2>
	 
<p>Use</p>
<pre><code>listView.getSelectionModel().getSelectedIndex();
</code>
</pre>	 </div>
